Q. How OneToMany is Mapped in the Database

Example Scenario
Suppose you have two entities:

User (one user)
Order (many orders per user)

Java Entity Mapping

@Entity
public class User {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    private String name;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "user")
    private List<Order> orders;
}

@Entity
public class Order {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    private String product;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "user_id") // Foreign key column in Order table
    private User user;
}

How This Looks in the Database

User Table:

id	                        name
1	                        Alice

Order Table:

id	                        product	                          user_id

1	                        Book	                           1
2	                        Laptop	                           1

Explanation:

The Order table has a column user_id (foreign key) that references the id column in the User
table.
This means each order "belongs" to one user, but a user can have many orders.

Summary:

(i)   In Java, you use @OneToMany on the parent and @ManyToOne on the child.
(ii)  In the database, the "many" side table (Order) has a foreign key column pointing to
      the "one" side (User).
(iii) This is how the relationship is mapped and enforced in the database [1].


Q.What will happen if you remove @ManyToOne mapping annotation from one or the other?

If you remove the @OneToMany or @ManyToOne annotation from your entity classes, several
important things will happen:

1. No Relationship Mapping:

(i) JPA/Hibernate will not know about the relationship between the two entities.
(ii) The framework will not automatically join or fetch related data for you.

2. Database Foreign Key:

(i) If you remove @ManyToOne from the child entity (e.g., Order), the foreign key column (user_id)
will not be created in the database table when you generate the schema.
(ii) If you remove @OneToMany from the parent entity (e.g., User), but keep @ManyToOne in the child,
the foreign key will still exist, but you won’t be able to easily access the list of related
entities from the parent side in Java.

3. Data Access:

(i) Without these annotations, you cannot use JPA to automatically fetch or save related entities.
For example, you won’t be able to do user.getOrders() if @OneToMany is missing.
You would have to manually write queries to fetch related data.

4. Referential Integrity:

(i) If you remove both annotations, there is no relationship at the Java or database level.
The tables will be independent, and you lose referential integrity (no foreign key constraint).


Summary Table

Annotation Removed	  Effect in Java Code	                 Effect in Database
@OneToMany	          Can't access child list from parent	  Foreign key still exists if
                                                              @ManyToOne is present in child
@ManyToOne	          Can't access parent from child	      No foreign key column in child
                                                              table
Both	              No relationship in code or DB	          No foreign key, tables are
                                                              independent


In short:

Removing these annotations breaks the automatic relationship mapping between your entities
and in your database schema. You lose the benefits of object-relational mapping and must
handle relationships manually



Q. What Happens If @ManyToOne Is Removed?

1. No Relationship Mapping in Java

The user field in Order is now just a regular field (not a JPA relationship).
JPA/Hibernate will not know that user is supposed to reference a User entity.
You cannot use order.getUser() to automatically fetch the related user entity.

2. Database Schema
If you generate the database schema from your entities, the user_id foreign key column
will not be created in the order table.
There will be no foreign key constraint between order and user.

3. Data Fetching
When you call orderRepository.findById(1L), JPA will only fetch the fields that are mapped.
The user field will be ignored (unless you manually map it as a column or another type).
You will not be able to fetch the related user with order.getUser()—it will either be null
or cause an error, depending on how you define the field.

4. Manual Handling Required
If you want to associate an order with a user, you would have to manage the relationship
yourself (e.g., by storing a userId field and manually querying the User table).


Example: What the Code Looks Like Without @ManyToOne


@Entity
public class Order {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    private String product;

    // No @ManyToOne annotation
    private Long userId; // Just a plain field, not a relationship
}

Fetching the user manually:


Optional<Order> orderOpt = orderRepository.findById(1L);
if (orderOpt.isPresent()) {
    Order order = orderOpt.get();
    Long userId = order.getUserId();
    // You must now manually fetch the user:
    Optional<User> userOpt = userRepository.findById(userId);
}


Summary Table

With @ManyToOne	                                       Without @ManyToOne

JPA manages relationship	                           No relationship in JPA
Foreign key in DB	                                   No foreign key in DB
order.getUser() works	                               order.getUser() is null/invalid
Automatic fetching	                                   Manual fetching required


Q. So if I pass by id, like findById(1) , then it will find the first id=1 , or what ?


Yes, if you use a method like findById(1) in Spring Data JPA, it will search for and return
the entity whose primary key (id) is 1—regardless of any relationships to other entities.

Here’s what happens:

(i)   findById(1) looks for a row in the table where the id column equals 1.
(ii)  If the entity exists, it returns that entity object.
(iii) If the entity does not exist, it returns Optional.empty() (or null if you use older JPA
methods).

Important:

(i) If you have removed relationship annotations (@OneToMany, @ManyToOne), findById(1) will
still work for finding the entity by its primary key.
(ii) However, you won’t be able to automatically access related entities (like
user.getOrders()) because JPA doesn’t know about the relationship anymore [1].


Summary:

(i)  findById(1) always finds the entity with id=1 in the specified table.
(ii) Relationships to other tables/entities are ignored if not mapped.

Q. What Query Does JPA Generate?

When you call orderRepository.findById(1L), JPA generates a SQL query like:

SELECT * FROM order WHERE id = 1;

a.The result includes the user_id column (foreign key).
b.JPA then uses the user_id to fetch the associated User entity if you access it (this is
called "lazy loading" by default).

If you access order.getUser(), JPA may issue another query:

SELECT * FROM user WHERE id = ?;

The ? is replaced with the value of user_id from the order row.

Summary Table

Action	                                        SQL Query Generated

findById(1L) on Order	                        SELECT * FROM order WHERE id = 1;
order.getUser() (if lazy)	                    SELECT * FROM user WHERE id = user_id;





